                                                                                <due></due>
                            <votes>0</votes>
                                    <watches>3</watches>
                                                                            <comments>
                            <comment id="481854" author="green" created="Fri, 19 Dec 2025 00:09:51 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Because of backports and the like we cannot depend on the version so we&apos;d have to devise some other ways like configure checks and the like.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;We can add a bit more infra to help that process I guess.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="481761" author="rread" created="Thu, 18 Dec 2025 13:25:36 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I thought feature flags were for runtime compatibility. Are there compile time #defines for identifying presence of features?   &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I also see api changes that I don&apos;t think would covered by feature flags, such as changing &lt;tt&gt;lov_pattern&lt;/tt&gt; from &lt;tt&gt;i32&lt;/tt&gt; to &lt;tt&gt;enum&lt;/tt&gt;&#160;a few months ago. Version numbers aren&apos;t perfect, but at least we can focus on supporting the latest version of each 2.x community branch. &lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="481657" author="green" created="Wed, 17 Dec 2025 16:54:27 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;We have long made a decision that &quot;lustre version&quot; is a meaningless concept because there are different branches from different places.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;As such it&apos;s all the compatibility flags that should be used to determine available functionality. Similarly at compile time availability of various defines should determine what&apos;s there, I imagine? Just looking at the version definitely looks very wrong here.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
